President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring April 8, 2010, as National D.A.R.E. Day. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of empowering young Americans to resist violence and substance abuse. It acknowledges the detrimental effects of drug abuse on individuals and families and calls for increased vigilance in recognizing and addressing the warning signs of drug and alcohol abuse. The proclamation also highlights the role of parents, educators, law enforcement officers, and mentors in promoting a healthy and drug-free lifestyle for children. It encourages community-based prevention and treatment programs, specifically mentioning the Drug Abuse Resistance Education (D.A.R.E.) program, which aims to teach young people to resist peer pressure and abstain from drugs, gangs, and violence. The proclamation concludes by urging all Americans to observe National D.A.R.E. Day with appropriate programs and activities.